I hate/love that song. its one of the few things that can make me jealous of a cartoon character,
but what it represents is so pure and sweet and kind and so incredibly rare that I can't help but weep with longing and smile with joy at the same time.
I feel you. When Stoick died, I couldn't even stop the shock because Dreamworks killed him after about 20 minutes from their reunion. I mean, where b is the justice in that?
Eurielle It's not even the context of the movie that does it for me. I crave the relationship the song describes.
I desire it desperately. I want it more than money, fame, property, or virtually anything else of this earth.

thus, my envy of those who have it, Stoick and Vilka included. But the reason I want it so much is that it is rare, precious, beautiful thing, so I can't help but smile when I "see" it, metaphorically speaking, in the song. therefore I weep with desperate longing for what this song is about while at the same time smiling with joy that I can at least see something so beautiful, even if it is beyond my grasp.
I hate the song for the jealousy and, likely forever, unfulfilled longing it stirs up in my heart, but I love it for its purity and sweetness.
Peter, you are such a glimmer of hope. This song goes straight to my heart. I've been battling severe chronic depression for the last 17 years.
That you recognized it's a bigger problem than most people will ever admit is wonderful.. Thank you.
Even more, you told the world that you've fought it yourself.
That is just amazing. Your music usually lifts me up, makes me smile, and even on occasion encourages me to sing.
I went to UO music school also.
Long story...Anyway, I'm grateful for your music,
your God given talent, and your willingness to let strangers into your life. That includes Evynne and Ashland too.
This song is the only thing that made me feel happy when I was 10 and I got left out of everything I was bullied even by my teacher it kept me out of subside thanks and I'm now 11 thanks again
I also am going through depression (3rd year now...yaay!), and also a ton of self-hatred.

Only recently have I begun to even slightly believe that I am a good person at the core, and it's really hard. Peter, I must say: THANKYOUTHANKYOUTHANKYOUSOOOOOMUCH!!!! this is exactly what I needed today! Love ya!
I was working at Barnes & Noble helping a customer and suddenly I stopped and said, "Is that... uhm... from the Hobbit?"
The customer thought I was nuts but a little Google searching confirmed that your new CD is on in-store play at Barnes & Nobles across the country!

Now I can't wait for your CD to come on! You're on our "Discover Great New Music" list! Also, hate to mention it but since you mention Amazon and iTunes, I thought I'd drop a quick plug for your album as available from BN and BN.com! Check it out!
Had this soundtrack in tape cassette form back when I was just a little girl.
Couldn't even tell you how many times I flipped it over and listened to one side after the other.
Knew all the songs by heart. My blanket was too small and the window of my room in the trailer was broken.

The nights were always so cold, lonely and bitter, but as long as I could lie there next to my big clunky radio and hear that music, everything was right and wonderful and the rest of the world, with all its cruelty and pain, disappeared.
Now I hear the same music on my laptop and phone and it touches my soul just as much.
Thank you so much for doing this medley. It brought tears to my eyes.
Such a beautiful reminder for me of how music can help us survive and there really can be miracles if you believe you can get through the night and make it through to the other side.
This version of the song is amazing. and i hadn't even heard of it until just a couple days ago.
have this song played at my funeral when i die. to say that this version is soulless is a pretty dumb statement.
obviously you don't have a soul if you can't enjoy the beauty of this man's fantastic version of an old song.

I think Peter interpreted the song in it's more joyous form rather than the bittersweet lament that most recognise the song as, which is fine, that's the beauty of old folks song's, everyone is entitled to take away their own meaning from a song like this.
The lyrics for The Parting Glass are extremely vague after-all.

Personally I'm not too keen on this version as I don't really relate to the more joyous uptempo side of the song. Much rather the covers by Glen Hansard, Ronnie Drew, Shane McGowan and of course Liam Clancy.
An opinion cannot be incorrect. An opinion is just that; an opinion.
( in my opinion ) Aside from that, the tune was written as a somber expression of mourning and with that, yes...this version fails to capture that although the harmonies were textbook.

Since cats first got their adorable claws into us about 9,500 years ago, humans have had a love affair with felines.
Today more than 80 million cats reside in U.S. homes, with an estimated three cats for every dog on the planet.
(Watch a video about the secret lives of cats.)
Yet there's still a lot we don't know about our feline friends??ncluding what they think of their owners.
John Bradshaw is a cat-behavior expert at the University of Bristol and the author of the new book Cat Sense.
After observing pet cats for several years, he's come to an intriguing conclusion: They don't really understand us the way dogs do
When a cat rolls over onto its back, it’s announcing to everyone in the general vicinity that its belly is open for business.
While I’m tempted to think that the cats enjoy this magical power they possess,
I wonder whether or not they actually appreciate the attention.
Free belly rubs from humans sounds like a great idea, until you plop down beside an open window to soak in the sun and a pack of bumbling humans come over and put their hands all over you.
I mean, personal space, come on.
It?? hard to deny that cats are the leaders of the Internet.
The cuddly creatures have infiltrated every corner of our digital world, making them practically inescapable.
And the best part is?
They have no idea. To them, every twitch of the nose or spontaneous nap time is just another part of their everyday routine.
The fact is, cats are completely unaware of their own cuteness, which is precisely what makes them so frigging adorable.
Let?? take a closer look at their impossibly squee mannerisms, shall we?
Why is it that, every time a cat wants something and they headbutt a part of your body, it’s considered cute, when every time I try it, it’s considered rude?
(Those double standards, man.)

Though it may look like they rsquo;re initiating affection, in actuality, they’re simply reminding you that you have something they need, whether it be food, water, or a big hand that can reach the itch they’ve trying to been scratch all day.

By now you've probably noticed that except when safely contained by quotes, Zampan? always steers clear of such questionable four-letter language.

This instance in particular proves that beneath all that cool psuedo-academic hogwash lurked a very passionate man who knew how important it was to say now and then, and say it loud too, relish its syllabic sweetness, its immigrant pride,
a great American epic word really, starting at the lower lip, often the very front of the lower lip,

before racing all the way to the back of the throat, where it finishes with a great blast, the concussive force of the K catching up then with the hush of the F already on its way, thus loading it with plenty of offense and edge and certainly ambiguity.

Some wounded thing--by the evidence, a large animal--had thrashed about in the underbrush; the jungle weeds were crushed down and the moss was lacerated; one patch of weeds was stained crimson.
